<div class="mb-4">
  <h3 id="crispr">CRISPR Cas9</h3>
  <p>
    CRISPR Cas9 is a tool for gene editing, which was discovered through
    microbiological research. It changed our understanding of the genes that
    control the rapid growth and survival of cancer cells. In the future, it may
    help with cancer diagnosis, treatment, or prevention.
  </p>
</div>
<div class="mb-4">
  <h3 id="histones">Histones</h3>
  <p>
    Histones are proteins that structurally support chromosomes and control gene
    activity. Research into these proteins and the impact of their gene
    modifications on the expression of genes has revealed its role on pediatric
    cancer. Specifically, in most cases of the pediatric brain tumor diffuse
    intrinsic pontine gliomas (DIPG) , mutations in the genes for a specific
    histone protein prevented a modification, which makes it a driver mutation
    for the tumor.
  </p>
</div>
<div class="mb-4">
  <h3 id="immunotherapy">Immunotherapies</h3>
  <p>
    Immunotherapy is a treatment that uses immune-system boosting drugs to fight
    cancer. Immunotherapy research has led to the development of new treatment
    methods in the past few years. One new treatment is chimeric antigen
    receptor (CAR) T-cell therapy, which has helped pediatric leukemia and
    lymphoma patients in various clinical trials.
  </p>
